WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.101 --> 00:00:02.637
Sometimes, all of the information

2
00:00:02.637 --> 00:00:05.773
that comes crashing into our lives is simply overwhelming.

3
00:00:05.773 --> 00:00:08.140
For some of you, it may even leave you depressed.

4
00:00:08.140 --> 00:00:11.063
No doubt, there is indeed a lot to consider these days.

5
00:00:11.063 --> 00:00:13.367
As an antidote to all of the seriousness,

6
00:00:13.367 --> 00:00:16.311
one woman has decided we need a good laugh at ourselves,

7
00:00:16.311 --> 00:00:18.444
and has taken it on as her life's work

8
00:00:18.444 --> 00:00:21.068
to do spiritually incorrect comedy.

9
00:00:21.068 --> 00:00:23.116
Although deeply spiritual by nature,

10
00:00:23.116 --> 00:00:27.057
Vanda Mikoloski believes laughter is another path to God.

11
00:00:29.887 --> 00:00:33.485 line:15% 
(mid-tempo jazz instrumental)

12
00:00:35.785 --> 00:00:37.024
How did you end up

13
00:00:37.024 --> 00:00:40.832
being an enlightenment comedian,

14
00:00:40.832 --> 00:00:44.682
showing at events such as the "What the bleep" conferences

15
00:00:44.682 --> 00:00:48.586
and that, and nonetheless, you say you're a bad girl,

16
00:00:48.586 --> 00:00:50.932
you're a naughty girl sometimes, at the same time.

17
00:00:50.932 --> 00:00:52.276
Let's get into your whole history,

18
00:00:52.276 --> 00:00:54.036
and how you link naughty girl with enlightenment,

19
00:00:54.036 --> 00:00:55.338
and now you're on stage.

20
00:00:55.338 --> 00:00:57.055
<v ->Oh, my gosh. That's a lot.</v>

21
00:00:57.055 --> 00:00:58.473
<v ->Yeah.
<v Vanda>Yeah!</v>

22
00:00:58.473 --> 00:00:59.849
<v Regina>How to begin?</v>

23
00:00:59.849 --> 00:01:03.422
<v ->Well, I've always loved the ideas of, you know,</v>

24
00:01:03.422 --> 00:01:05.300
what are we doing here?

25
00:01:05.300 --> 00:01:06.462
Why are we here?

26
00:01:06.462 --> 00:01:09.737
What is this trap called the human predicament?

27
00:01:09.737 --> 00:01:11.155
Is it a trap?

28
00:01:11.155 --> 00:01:14.612
Are we just these mechanistic entities,

29
00:01:14.612 --> 00:01:18.234
linear, temporal, designed to survive

30
00:01:18.234 --> 00:01:19.368
and then die?

31
00:01:19.368 --> 00:01:21.494
Or, is there something other?

32
00:01:21.494 --> 00:01:23.176
And I've always pondered that.

33
00:01:23.176 --> 00:01:27.526
I was raised in strict Roman Catholicism.

34
00:01:27.526 --> 00:01:31.679
That gave me something that was dogmatic

35
00:01:31.679 --> 00:01:35.213
and not inclusive of other belief systems,

36
00:01:35.213 --> 00:01:39.392
for me to consider other belief systems, you know?

37
00:01:39.392 --> 00:01:42.095
Then, you know when you're a kid,

38
00:01:42.095 --> 00:01:44.150
how you just marvel at things?

39
00:01:44.150 --> 00:01:46.735
My brother and I, we had plenty of nature around us,

40
00:01:46.735 --> 00:01:50.767
and we could just lie in fields and wonder,

41
00:01:50.767 --> 00:01:54.318
you know, at the awesome magnificence of all of it.

42
00:01:54.318 --> 00:01:56.196
And I always knew, I think kids kinda know,

43
00:01:56.196 --> 00:02:01.049
that that patriarchal, punitive God figure

44
00:02:01.049 --> 00:02:04.782
that they were telling me was the creator

45
00:02:04.782 --> 00:02:07.320
and intelligence behind all this, just didn't really,

46
00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:08.589
you know, that didn't fit.

47
00:02:08.589 --> 00:02:10.637
So I set out on a journey.

48
00:02:10.637 --> 00:02:14.603
I had a rebellious older brother,

49
00:02:14.603 --> 00:02:17.780
we did drugs from a really early age.

50
00:02:17.780 --> 00:02:19.650
So I did acid at around 11.

51
00:02:19.650 --> 00:02:23.362
My brain was so clean that I had a great little acid trip,

52
00:02:23.362 --> 00:02:26.583
and saw that I was one with everything.

53
00:02:26.583 --> 00:02:30.851
And I don't recommend it for all you 11 year olds out there,

54
00:02:30.851 --> 00:02:34.902
But it was a sensation, or a sensibility,

55
00:02:34.902 --> 00:02:37.825
that I chased my whole life after that.

56
00:02:37.825 --> 00:02:40.630
It's like, what is that unity that I know is there?

57
00:02:40.630 --> 00:02:45.003
And you never get that sense of

58
00:02:45.003 --> 00:02:48.395
"I am whole, complete and perfect", and then forget it.

59
00:02:48.395 --> 00:02:50.112
No matter if you're tripping, or not.

60
00:02:50.112 --> 00:02:52.661
I just knew, oh my god, my parents have been misinformed.

61
00:02:52.661 --> 00:02:55.328
They think there's something awry, and there isn't.

62
00:02:55.328 --> 00:02:56.746
I'm perfect.

63
00:02:56.746 --> 00:02:59.669
So, there was that, and then just growing up,

64
00:02:59.669 --> 00:03:02.111
and watching societal systems,

65
00:03:02.111 --> 00:03:03.925
and you see in the background,

66
00:03:03.925 --> 00:03:07.711
like in the wallpaper of education, religion, everything.

67
00:03:07.711 --> 00:03:10.004
Don't be you, because you suck.

68
00:03:10.004 --> 00:03:12.489
You know, that's like everywhere in the background.

69
00:03:12.489 --> 00:03:15.252
In almost any system we have,

70
00:03:15.252 --> 00:03:19.732
any of the largely male-dominated systems that work...

71
00:03:19.732 --> 00:03:22.078
Not working, you know?

72
00:03:22.078 --> 00:03:24.853
And there's that don't be you because you suck, thing.

73
00:03:24.853 --> 00:03:26.989
<v ->Well, it keeps the money flowing.
<v Vanda>Yeah.</v>

74
00:03:26.989 --> 00:03:29.380
<v Regina>If you suck, you have to keep buying more</v>

75
00:03:29.410 --> 00:03:30.878
to bolster yourself.

76
00:03:30.878 --> 00:03:32.064
<v ->How won't I suck?</v>

77
00:03:32.064 --> 00:03:33.099
<v ->(laughing) Right.</v>

78
00:03:33.099 --> 00:03:36.328
<v ->How much is that gonna cost? Right, exactly.</v>

79
00:03:36.328 --> 00:03:40.954
So, you know, there's that amazing thing in comedy.

80
00:03:40.954 --> 00:03:42.895
A lot of comics come from despair,

81
00:03:42.895 --> 00:03:45.572
and depression and pain, and suffering and all that.

82
00:03:45.572 --> 00:03:48.591
And enlightenment, similar thing.

83
00:03:48.591 --> 00:03:52.121
If you notice, the guys like Eckhart Tolle or Byron Katie,

84
00:03:52.121 --> 00:03:54.788
they all hit that point where they were one step away

85
00:03:54.788 --> 00:03:57.667
from suicidal despair and one step away from enlightenment,

86
00:03:57.667 --> 00:03:59.267
and they went that way.

87
00:03:59.267 --> 00:04:01.454
Some of us played on the edges

88
00:04:01.454 --> 00:04:04.099
of the threshold of sanity for a while,

89
00:04:04.099 --> 00:04:06.605
you know, and anesthetized ourselves.

90
00:04:06.605 --> 00:04:07.332
I did.

91
00:04:07.332 --> 00:04:09.048
<v ->Well, you did. Yeah, and that was in New York,</v>

92
00:04:09.048 --> 00:04:11.015
in the early days in comedy?

93
00:04:11.015 --> 00:04:12.769
<v ->Yeah.
<v Regina>Yeah.</v>

94
00:04:12.769 --> 00:04:15.601
<v Vanda>Yeah. And so I was anesthetizing myself,</v>

95
00:04:15.601 --> 00:04:16.871
very self-destructive behavior,

96
00:04:16.871 --> 00:04:20.309
but hanging out with some really interesting and fun people.

97
00:04:20.309 --> 00:04:24.412
And the body was so resilient in my 20s, you know?

98
00:04:24.412 --> 00:04:25.638
So there's that.

99
00:04:25.638 --> 00:04:29.206
But at some point, you know,

100
00:04:29.206 --> 00:04:32.666
like my boyfriend, Eckhart Tolle, says,

101
00:04:32.666 --> 00:04:36.868
all addictions begin with pain and ultimately end with pain.

102
00:04:36.868 --> 00:04:39.513
The middle part can be really, really fun though.

103
00:04:39.513 --> 00:04:41.006
I'll tell you, it can be really fun.

104
00:04:41.006 --> 00:04:43.964
Just that part alone, that's really fun.

105
00:04:43.964 --> 00:04:46.617
And it does end with a pain,

106
00:04:46.617 --> 00:04:49.849
and at some point, I said, why am I killing myself?

107
00:04:49.849 --> 00:04:54.008
At about age 40, I said, why am I...

108
00:04:54.008 --> 00:04:57.112
Like, the idea that there might be an issue

109
00:04:57.112 --> 00:05:01.753
underneath all of this stuff that I'm anesthetizing.

110
00:05:01.753 --> 00:05:05.440
I just one day said, oh, I'm not...

111
00:05:05.440 --> 00:05:10.247
Maybe I'm not just a self-destructive jerk who's...

112
00:05:10.247 --> 00:05:13.465
completely irresponsible.

113
00:05:13.465 --> 00:05:15.363
Maybe I'm anesthetizing

114
00:05:15.363 --> 00:05:18.243
something I don't wanna see in myself.

115
00:05:18.243 --> 00:05:19.779
Something I don't wanna feel.

116
00:05:19.779 --> 00:05:21.454
You know, and I started doing a lot of work,

117
00:05:21.454 --> 00:05:24.355
a lot of spiritual work, transformational work,

118
00:05:24.355 --> 00:05:28.068
and I got to...

119
00:05:28.068 --> 00:05:29.517
One of the core things

120
00:05:29.517 --> 00:05:32.226
in my mechanistic knee-jerk personality

121
00:05:32.226 --> 00:05:34.850
is, you know, my brother, who was the love of my life,

122
00:05:34.850 --> 00:05:36.429
died when I was 13.

123
00:05:36.429 --> 00:05:37.869
And then my dad died.

124
00:05:37.869 --> 00:05:38.871
He drowned,

125
00:05:38.871 --> 00:05:41.232
and then my dad died in a car accident a few years later.

126
00:05:41.232 --> 00:05:43.511
Drug-related, alcohol-related.

127
00:05:43.511 --> 00:05:47.922
And I just developed early on,

128
00:05:47.922 --> 00:05:50.752
this defensiveness about,

129
00:05:50.752 --> 00:05:52.225
I don't want my heart to get broken anymore.

130
00:05:52.225 --> 00:05:55.009
I don't want to feel that kind of pain anymore.

131
00:05:55.009 --> 00:05:58.379
And so I lived my whole life doing that.

132
00:05:58.379 --> 00:06:00.278
Here I am, 48, not married,

133
00:06:00.278 --> 00:06:01.878
but not by my own choice.

134
00:06:01.878 --> 00:06:03.115
Single.

135
00:06:03.115 --> 00:06:06.070
And so I'm just, at 40, I just for the last eight years

136
00:06:06.070 --> 00:06:08.286
I've been working out some of those issues

137
00:06:08.286 --> 00:06:11.699
that have had me protecting myself for so long.

138
00:06:11.699 --> 00:06:13.000
<v ->And you really,</v>

139
00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:14.909
you've thrown yourself into it at times, too.

140
00:06:14.909 --> 00:06:16.662
You were with Ramtha, right?
<v Vanda>Mm-hmm.</v>

141
00:06:16.662 --> 00:06:19.229
<v Regina>Spent a good amount of time with her.</v>

142
00:06:19.229 --> 00:06:20.648
And you were saying off camera,

143
00:06:20.648 --> 00:06:23.378
you're listening to every audio tape and CD in the car,

144
00:06:23.378 --> 00:06:26.194
going here and there, so you were really searching.

145
00:06:26.194 --> 00:06:26.962
<v ->Yeah.</v>

146
00:06:26.962 --> 00:06:28.679
<v ->This wasn't a passive thing for you.</v>

147
00:06:28.679 --> 00:06:33.234
<v ->Mm-mm. No, I love having those ah-has.</v>

148
00:06:33.234 --> 00:06:34.855
They're my favorite things.

149
00:06:34.855 --> 00:06:37.041
Second only to ha-has.

150
00:06:37.041 --> 00:06:38.460
<v ->Ha-has, right.</v>

151
00:06:38.460 --> 00:06:41.756
What did the ah-has do to your ha-has, by the way?

152
00:06:41.756 --> 00:06:43.281
During that period of time.

