00:20:39.991 --> 00:20:42.220
you think, huh, I wonder how many more eons we'll do that,

512
00:20:42.220 --> 00:20:44.748
before we come up with something a little more interesting.

513
00:20:44.748 --> 00:20:49.611
You know, a little more fun or creative.

514
00:20:49.611 --> 00:20:51.713
<v ->Yeah, it's getting to be an old story.</v>

515
00:20:51.713 --> 00:20:53.526
So looking at all of these stories,

516
00:20:53.526 --> 00:20:55.667
what to you is one of the most...

517
00:20:55.667 --> 00:20:58.123
What are some of the absurdities about human nature

518
00:20:58.123 --> 00:21:01.056
that you really like to get on in your acts?

519
00:21:01.056 --> 00:21:03.723
The whole notion of, you know, peace, love, harmony,

520
00:21:03.723 --> 00:21:06.016
oneness and so forth.

521
00:21:06.016 --> 00:21:07.733
Okay? Where do you really go?

522
00:21:07.733 --> 00:21:10.986
What do you find really ironic or absurd about all of us?

523
00:21:10.986 --> 00:21:13.098
<v ->You talking about the angel and dolphin crowd?</v>

524
00:21:13.098 --> 00:21:15.125
<v ->There you go. Whatever.</v>

525
00:21:15.125 --> 00:21:17.759
<v ->I call them the angel and dolphin crowd.</v>

526
00:21:17.759 --> 00:21:21.247
Yeah, that you can't be good without being bad.

527
00:21:21.247 --> 00:21:23.508
You can't be good without accepting your badness,

528
00:21:23.508 --> 00:21:24.746
you know what I mean?

529
00:21:24.746 --> 00:21:26.942
Like, that's something I really harp on onstage,

530
00:21:26.942 --> 00:21:28.681
because I was, like,

531
00:21:28.681 --> 00:21:30.238
my personality was rebellious.

532
00:21:30.238 --> 00:21:33.341
I was a bad girl, you know.

533
00:21:33.341 --> 00:21:38.035
So I love to include that.

534
00:21:38.035 --> 00:21:39.571
I have to admit right upfront

535
00:21:39.571 --> 00:21:43.005
that I don't feel like I'm spiritual enough.

536
00:21:43.005 --> 00:21:44.776
Like, you ever feel like that?

537
00:21:44.776 --> 00:21:46.376
Like, I don't know.

538
00:21:46.376 --> 00:21:48.370
All my spiritual friends, they're raising their energy

539
00:21:48.370 --> 00:21:50.385
from their lower chakras

540
00:21:50.385 --> 00:21:53.905
up to their heart chakra.

541
00:21:53.905 --> 00:21:57.010
My first chakra is like my favorite chakra so far.

542
00:21:57.010 --> 00:21:59.698
(audience laughter)

543
00:21:59.698 --> 00:22:01.948
Do you know what I mean? I love that chakra.

544
00:22:01.948 --> 00:22:05.067
The others are nice, but I really like that one.

545
00:22:05.067 --> 00:22:06.579
(audience laughter)

546
00:22:06.579 --> 00:22:08.615
I have a line in my act where I say,

547
00:22:08.615 --> 00:22:09.937
I quote John Lennon.

548
00:22:09.937 --> 00:22:11.912
I say, John Lennon, the great Beatle, said,

549
00:22:11.912 --> 00:22:15.163
"We are all Hitler, we are all Jesus Christ."

550
00:22:15.163 --> 00:22:17.883
Now, I do think it's the ratio that counts,

551
00:22:17.883 --> 00:22:19.946
is my little line.

552
00:22:19.946 --> 00:22:23.917
But people say, don't say that! Don't say that!

553
00:22:23.917 --> 00:22:25.348
Because some people just--

554
00:22:25.348 --> 00:22:29.508
Or I say, I'm a liar, a cheat, a tramp and a thief.

555
00:22:29.508 --> 00:22:30.618
And they go, you're not that.

556
00:22:30.618 --> 00:22:32.271
I'm like, yes, I am.

557
00:22:32.271 --> 00:22:33.380
But you're not that anymore!

558
00:22:33.380 --> 00:22:34.703
You've evolved past that, haven't you?

559
00:22:34.703 --> 00:22:36.100
No, you're a liar, too.

560
00:22:36.100 --> 00:22:38.052
You just haven't done the work. Just look.

561
00:22:38.052 --> 00:22:39.748
You're probably a cheat and a thief,

562
00:22:39.748 --> 00:22:40.793
I don't know what you are,

563
00:22:40.793 --> 00:22:44.942
but the flavor of your humanness, look.

564
00:22:44.942 --> 00:22:48.962
Keep looking, you'll find it. It's in there, you know?

565
00:22:48.962 --> 00:22:52.334
But it's like, the people who want to think positive,

566
00:22:52.334 --> 00:22:54.509
the only reason they're thinking that way

567
00:22:54.509 --> 00:22:56.579
is because they're really negative.

568
00:22:56.579 --> 00:22:58.392
Do you know what I mean? There's that whole duality.

569
00:22:58.392 --> 00:22:59.896
<v ->When you really have to push toward that.</v>

570
00:22:59.896 --> 00:23:00.877
<v ->Yeah.
<v Regina>Yeah.</v>

571
00:23:00.877 --> 00:23:03.688
<v Vanda>Yeah, and...</v>

572
00:23:03.688 --> 00:23:05.442
<v ->So you're saying that there's an inherent lack</v>

573
00:23:05.442 --> 00:23:08.413
of acceptance of one's other side,

574
00:23:08.413 --> 00:23:10.924
if you're only putting forth a positive face.

575
00:23:10.924 --> 00:23:14.359
<v ->Yeah. We can't-- and then whatever we resist in another,</v>

576
00:23:14.359 --> 00:23:16.196
we strengthen in ourselves.

577
00:23:16.196 --> 00:23:17.729
Like, so there's certain things

578
00:23:17.729 --> 00:23:20.673
I can't be with in other people, you know?

579
00:23:20.673 --> 00:23:23.766
And then, mastering that art of going,

580
00:23:23.766 --> 00:23:25.697
where am I that way?

581
00:23:25.697 --> 00:23:28.683
Hmm, because it looks like them, it doesn't look like me.

582
00:23:28.683 --> 00:23:32.872
Or I do a more sophisticated version of that.

583
00:23:32.872 --> 00:23:34.800
Or something, you know?

584
00:23:34.800 --> 00:23:36.491
<v ->Yeah, I can't look like that.</v>

585
00:23:36.491 --> 00:23:38.624
<v ->Yeah, yeah.</v>

586
00:23:38.624 --> 00:23:40.853
<v ->Well, what was it like with two comedians together?</v>

587
00:23:40.853 --> 00:23:42.336
Can you tell us a little bit,

588
00:23:42.336 --> 00:23:43.754
without getting too personal, of course,

589
00:23:43.754 --> 00:23:45.269
about your journey with Bill Maher,

590
00:23:45.269 --> 00:23:47.285
and that time together?

591
00:23:47.285 --> 00:23:51.743
<v ->Bill Maher was great. A strict disciplinarian.</v>

592
00:23:51.743 --> 00:23:54.996
He was like, "I want you to do good comedy,

593
00:23:54.996 --> 00:23:57.898
"I don't want you to do typically female comedy."

594
00:23:57.898 --> 00:24:00.895
Because women sometimes, in comedy,

595
00:24:00.895 --> 00:24:03.767
take a point of view where they're disempowered,

596
00:24:03.767 --> 00:24:06.697
and they rally favor with the women in the audience

597
00:24:06.697 --> 00:24:09.971
in order to, they curry favor with the women in the audience

598
00:24:09.971 --> 00:24:14.472
in order to get agreement on a point of view.

599
00:24:14.472 --> 00:24:15.518
<v ->Victim.</v>

600
00:24:15.518 --> 00:24:19.208
<v ->Yeah! So he encouraged me never to write female comedy,</v>

601
00:24:19.208 --> 00:24:22.675
to always write experientially as a human being,

602
00:24:22.675 --> 00:24:24.765
you know, and some of that's female.

603
00:24:24.765 --> 00:24:27.506
But, and to not, you know, like women tend to generalize,

604
00:24:27.506 --> 00:24:29.330
men are like this.

605
00:24:29.330 --> 00:24:31.655
No! The guy that I saw was like this.

606
00:24:31.655 --> 00:24:33.533
Or something like that, you know?

607
00:24:33.533 --> 00:24:36.071
So he was really strict about that.

608
00:24:36.071 --> 00:24:40.118
Too strict sometimes, my girlfriends got mad at him.

609
00:24:40.118 --> 00:24:43.889
But he was a great, he held the bar really high for me

610
00:24:43.889 --> 00:24:46.707
when I was just starting out in comedy.

611
00:24:46.707 --> 00:24:49.218
<v ->So it sounds like he was a really wonderful mentor.</v>

612
00:24:49.218 --> 00:24:50.513
<v ->Absolutely.</v>

613
00:24:50.513 --> 00:24:52.113
<v ->And he sounds absolutely brilliant, too.</v>

614
00:24:52.113 --> 00:24:54.737
<v ->He's brilliant, yeah! Brilliant.</v>

615
00:24:54.737 --> 00:24:55.921
<v ->And a lot of heart?</v>

616
00:24:55.921 --> 00:24:57.734
<v ->Yeah. Yeah, he's got a deep...</v>

617
00:24:57.734 --> 00:25:00.678
You know, some people would disagree.

618
00:25:00.678 --> 00:25:03.557
But we went to see the movie,

619
00:25:03.557 --> 00:25:07.088
what was that movie with the alien?

620
00:25:07.088 --> 00:25:09.434
<v ->Which one? That one that pops out of the chest, or...</v>

621
00:25:09.434 --> 00:25:10.800
<v ->No, no. No, no.</v>

622
00:25:10.800 --> 00:25:12.709
You know, the 80s movie.

623
00:25:12.709 --> 00:25:13.455
<v Voiceover>"E.T."</v>

624
00:25:13.455 --> 00:25:14.703
<v Regina>Oh, "E.T."</v>

625
00:25:14.703 --> 00:25:16.976
<v Vanda>"E.T."! And, you know, Bill cried.</v>

626
00:25:16.976 --> 00:25:21.542
Now a friend of mine said he cried because he wasn't in it.

627
00:25:21.542 --> 00:25:24.431
<v ->No, I think when somebody is that, as we see him today,</v>

628
00:25:24.431 --> 00:25:28.027
when someone's that angrily trying to get their point across

629
00:25:28.027 --> 00:25:30.466
that's usually because there's a really broken heart

630
00:25:30.466 --> 00:25:32.182
underneath all of that.

631
00:25:32.182 --> 00:25:34.020
Do you find that with comedians in general?

632
00:25:34.020 --> 00:25:36.089
<v ->Oh, now you're being all Barbara Walters on me. (laughs)</v>

633
00:25:36.089 --> 00:25:39.289
<v ->I'm sorry! Well, seriously.</v>

634
00:25:39.289 --> 00:25:41.240
Well, not seriously, okay?

635
00:25:41.240 --> 00:25:43.436
<v ->Yeah. Yeah.</v>

636
00:25:43.436 --> 00:25:47.768
Oh, I think we're all walking wounded, you know?

637
00:25:47.768 --> 00:25:51.896
And that oftentimes, people who make it to fame

638
00:25:51.896 --> 00:25:55.508
are so driven by an unconscious perception

639
00:25:55.508 --> 00:26:00.508
of themselves as, I mean, why would anyone do that?

640
00:26:00.545 --> 00:26:04.226
Crawl through the ladder of this hierarchical town

641
00:26:04.226 --> 00:26:07.127
in order to stand on the top of the trash heap

642
00:26:07.127 --> 00:26:08.684
we call Hollywood,

643
00:26:08.684 --> 00:26:10.455
and reflect culture back to itself.

644
00:26:10.455 --> 00:26:12.662
Why would anyone be driven to do that?

645
00:26:12.662 --> 00:26:14.817
There has to be, like, I don't know,

646
00:26:14.817 --> 00:26:18.361
overcompensation for some perceived lack,

647
00:26:18.361 --> 00:26:20.577
or something like that.

648
00:26:20.577 --> 00:26:21.878
You know, I don't know.

649
00:26:21.878 --> 00:26:26.482
Very rarely is it because I care to contribute

650
00:26:26.482 --> 00:26:29.237
to my fellow men, you know, and women.

651
00:26:29.237 --> 00:26:30.283
I don't know.

652
00:26:30.283 --> 00:26:31.648
<v Regina>But you do now.</v>

653
00:26:31.648 --> 00:26:33.461
That is what you're doing now, isn't it?

654
00:26:33.461 --> 00:26:34.805
<v ->Actually, you know, now it is.</v>

655
00:26:34.805 --> 00:26:38.155
Now it is, and...

656
00:26:38.155 --> 00:26:40.821
Yeah, I didn't wanna be in nightclubs again.

657
00:26:40.821 --> 00:26:42.613
And then, when my brother was involved

658
00:26:42.613 --> 00:26:46.272
with the movie "What The Bleep Do We Know",

659
00:26:46.272 --> 00:26:49.897
I decided, if I could really--

660
00:26:49.897 --> 00:26:52.138
FIrst of all, I thought about my life

661
00:26:52.138 --> 00:26:54.097
as Eckhart Tolle talks about it,

662
00:26:54.097 --> 00:26:56.126
this little dash between the year of your birth

663
00:26:56.126 --> 00:26:58.654
and the year of your death on your gravestone.

664
00:26:58.654 --> 00:27:01.235
And if you think about that, I want a kick-ass hyphen.

665
00:27:01.235 --> 00:27:03.667
You know, I want a hyphen that's really great.

666
00:27:03.667 --> 00:27:08.223
You know, and so do I want to be on my deathbed going,

667
00:27:08.223 --> 00:27:10.749
you know, I never really fulfilled that dream in Hollywood

668
00:27:10.749 --> 00:27:12.915
that I just loved, I loved comedy.

669
00:27:12.915 --> 00:27:15.421
I mean, when I work with my other comedians,

670
00:27:15.421 --> 00:27:18.780
we get together, the "Spiritually Incorrect" comedians,

671
00:27:18.780 --> 00:27:23.549
and we just revel in the, how to turn a phrase.

672
00:27:23.549 --> 00:27:27.026
It's just so much fun. The technique of comedy itself.

673
00:27:27.026 --> 00:27:30.375
And the edge of it, and what it expresses.

674
00:27:30.375 --> 00:27:32.529
It's just delightful for us.

675
00:27:32.529 --> 00:27:35.804
So I love comedy, I love making people laugh.

676
00:27:35.804 --> 00:27:40.626
I love laughing myself. I love the edge of truth.

677
00:27:40.626 --> 00:27:44.209
And I love that

678
00:27:44.209 --> 00:27:46.619
there's something very spiritual in laughing.

679
00:27:46.619 --> 00:27:49.270
Like my old guru Ramtha used to say,

680
00:27:49.270 --> 00:27:51.728
"Whatever you can't laugh at owns you."

681
00:27:51.728 --> 00:27:55.163
You know, so you look at, none of us,

682
00:27:55.163 --> 00:27:59.136
me and my comics, we're not sacred,

683
00:27:59.136 --> 00:28:01.876
reverent about anything.

684
00:28:01.876 --> 00:28:05.255
I haven't found a threshold yet.

685
00:28:05.255 --> 00:28:08.320
It's this funny thing, this whole enlightened eating thing.

686
00:28:08.320 --> 00:28:09.831
I was at Whole Foods not too long ago,

687
00:28:09.831 --> 00:28:11.996
and I'm standing in front of the egg selection, right?

688
00:28:11.996 --> 00:28:14.855
And I'm looking at all the vast array of eggs.

689
00:28:14.855 --> 00:28:16.316
It's mind-boggling, right?

690
00:28:16.316 --> 00:28:20.049
There's, like, crappy cheap eggs from caged hens,

691
00:28:20.049 --> 00:28:22.534
you know, just resentful passive-aggressive,

692
00:28:22.534 --> 00:28:24.806
here's your damn egg, yeah, take it!

693
00:28:24.806 --> 00:28:26.086
(audience laughter)

694
00:28:26.086 --> 00:28:28.902
I mean, life is hell!

695
00:28:28.902 --> 00:28:31.313
And then there's cage-free,

696
00:28:31.313 --> 00:28:33.798
and then there's another distinction, free-range,

697
00:28:33.798 --> 00:28:35.910
and then there's another distinction beyond that

698
00:28:35.910 --> 00:28:38.277
which is fully self-realized.

699
00:28:38.277 --> 00:28:40.997
(audience laughter)

700
00:28:40.997 --> 00:28:43.248
They're like, you know what?

701
00:28:43.248 --> 00:28:45.573
These eggs are like, I came first!

702
00:28:45.573 --> 00:28:48.847
(audience laughter)

703
00:28:51.047 --> 00:28:53.116
And then there's another distinction.

704
00:28:53.116 --> 00:28:55.249
The ones I like, I really like the eggs

705
00:28:55.249 --> 00:28:58.619
that actually had crappy circumstances, they were caged,

706
00:28:58.619 --> 00:29:01.638
but they weren't victims of their circumstance.

707
00:29:01.638 --> 00:29:03.259
Right? Right?

708
00:29:03.259 --> 00:29:05.531
(audience laughing and cheering)

709
00:29:05.531 --> 00:29:07.323
Yeah, they saw the movie "The Secret",

